litical actors during the interwar period. Ortiz’s study reinterprets the political origins of the "Second" New Deal and Roosevelt’s electoral triumph of 1936, adding depth not only to our understanding of these events and the political climate surrounding them, but to common perceptions of veterans and their organizations. In describing veteran politics and the competitive dynamics between the AL and the VFW, Ortiz details the rise of organized veterans as a powerful interest group in modern American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aNew Deal, 1933-1939. 0aProtest movementszWashington (D.C.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxEducationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteranszUnited StatesxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xVeteranszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aOrtiz.  aVFW.  abetween.  acompetitive.  adescribing.  adetails.  adynamics.  agroup.  ainterest.  amodern.  aorganized.  apolitics.  apowerful.  arise.  aveteran.  aveterans.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762561423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762561/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK